## Project Structure

```
src/
├── Domain/           # Aggregates, entities, value objects, domain events
├── Application/      # Use case handlers, ports, DTOs — organised by feature
│   └── Features/
├── Infrastructure/   # EF Core, external services, repository implementations
└── Presentation/     # Minimal API entrypoint

tests/
├── Domain.Tests/     # Unit tests for domain objects
├── Application.Tests/ # Integration tests per slice
└── Architecture.Tests/ # ArchUnitNET dependency-direction tests
```

## Makefile Targets

| Target | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `make build` | Compile all projects (Release mode) |
| `make test` | Run all test suites |
| `make coverage` | Run tests with coverage gate; fails if <90% |
| `make lint` | Check code formatting (`dotnet format --verify-no-changes`) |
| `make clean` | Remove `bin/`, `obj/`, and coverage results |
| `make sbom` | Generate Software Bill of Materials (`sbom.cdx.json`) |

## Architecture Rules

The scaffold enforces Clean Architecture dependency rules via `Architecture.Tests`:

- **Domain**: no outward dependencies, no framework references
- **Application**: depends only on Domain; defines ports/interfaces
- **Infrastructure**: implements Application ports; does not leak into Domain or Application
- **Presentation**: depends only on Application; never directly on Domain or Infrastructure

Violating these rules causes `make test` to fail with a descriptive error.

## Adding a Feature

1. Create `src/Application/Features/<FeatureName>/` folder
2. Add `<FeatureName>Command.cs` (or `Query.cs`) and corresponding handler
3. Add validator using FluentValidation
4. Add integration test in `tests/Application.Tests/Features/<FeatureName>/`
5. Wire endpoint in `src/Presentation/Program.cs`

## Security

### Secret Scanning

GitLeaks is configured in `.gitleaks.toml`. To run locally:

```bash
gitleaks detect --source . --config .gitleaks.toml
```

Pre-commit hook setup:

```bash
# Install gitleaks: https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks
# Add to .git/hooks/pre-commit:
gitleaks protect --staged
```

### Vulnerability Scanning

Dependencies are automatically scanned by Dependabot (see `.github/dependabot.yml`).

To scan locally:

```bash
dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive
```

Builds **fail** for Critical/High severity vulnerabilities unless an exception is recorded.

### SBOM

Generate a Software Bill of Materials:

```bash
make sbom
# Produces: sbom.cdx.json (CycloneDX format)
```

### Runtime Hardening Checklist

Before deploying to production:

- [ ] Remove development `appsettings.Development.json` overrides
- [ ] Enable HTTPS redirection and HSTS
- [ ] Disable detailed error pages (`app.UseExceptionHandler`)
- [ ] Validate all environment variables / secrets are provided via Secret Manager or Vault (never committed to source)
- [ ] Review and restrict CORS origins
- [ ] Enable rate limiting middleware
- [ ] Validate authentication and authorisation policies cover all endpoints
- [ ] Run `make sbom` and verify no Critical/High CVEs

## Performance Benchmarks

The scaffold includes an opt-in BenchmarkDotNet project at `tests/Benchmarks/`.

```bash
make benchmark
```

Suggested targets (adjust per SLA):

| Metric | Target |
|--------|--------|
| p95 latency | <200ms |
| p99 latency | <500ms |
| Throughput | ≥1000 RPS (simple endpoints) |

## Observability

The Presentation layer is pre-wired with:

- **OpenTelemetry** tracing (OTLP exporter configured via environment variable)
- **Prometheus** metrics endpoint at `/metrics`
- **Grafana** dashboard template at `docs/dashboards/app-dashboard.json`

Environment variables:

| Variable | Default | Description |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` | *(unset)* | OTLP collector endpoint |
| `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` | `{{SOLUTION_NAME}}` | Service name in traces |

